-- Japanese Stock Futures, Australia Shares Gain on U.S. Retail Sales, Dollar
-- B y   A k i k o   I k e d a
-- 2010-11-15T23:25:07Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-15/japanese-stock-futures-australia-shares-gain-on-u-s-retail-sales-dollar.html
Japanese  stock   futures  and
Australian shares rose after U.S. retail sales climbed more than
expected and the dollar advanced to a six-week high.  American depositary receipts of Nissan Motor Co., a
Japanese carmaker that counts North America as its largest
market, jumped 1.2 percent from the closing share price in Tokyo.
Those of Sony Corp., the maker of Bravia televisions, gained 0.2
percent. Australia and New Zealand Banking Group Ltd.,
Australia’s third-largest bank by market value, jumped 2.3
percent after the Wall Street Journal reported it may quit its
bid for Korea Exchange Bank.  Futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225 Stock Average  expiring in
December closed at 9,865 in Chicago yesterday, compared with
9,830 in Singapore. They were bid in the pre-market at 9,840 in
Osaka, Japan, at 8:05 a.m. local time. Australia’s S&P/ASX 200
Index gained 0.3 percent today. New Zealand’s NZX 50 Index was
little changed in Wellington.  “The retail sales were unexpectedly good,” said  Fumiyuki Nakanishi , a strategist at Tokyo-based SMBC Friend Securities Co.
“The market should take the strong sales figures ahead of the
Christmas shopping season positively. The weaker yen should
boost the market. Hopes that companies will raise their profit
forecasts should increase.”  Futures on the  Standard & Poor’s 500 Index  slid 0.2 percent
today. In New York, the index retreated 0.1 percent yesterday as
increased criticism of the Federal Reserve’s plan to stimulate
growth and concern that a swelling federal deficit will lead to
higher borrowing costs drove Treasury yields higher. Yields on
30-year Treasuries rose to 4.41 percent,　the highest intraday
level since May.  U.S. Retail Sales  Sales at U.S. retailers climbed 1.2 percent in October, the
biggest gain in seven months, according to data from the
Commerce Department issued yesterday in Washington. That
exceeded the highest forecast among economists surveyed by
Bloomberg News.  The dollar reached 83.25 yen, the highest level since Oct.
6, compared with 82.75 at the close of stock trading in Tokyo
yesterday. A weaker yen boosts the value of overseas income at
Japanese companies when converted into their home currency.  The  MSCI Asia Pacific Index  has increased 9.3 percent
through yesterday in 2010, compared with gains of 7.4 percent by
the S&P 500 and 7.3 percent by the  Stoxx Europe 600 Index .
Stocks in the Asian benchmark are valued at an average 14.4
times estimated  earnings , compared with 14.1 times for the S&P
500 and 12.2 times for the Stoxx 600.  Copper futures for March delivery climbed 0.7 percent in
New York yesterday.  To contact the reporter for this story:
 Akiko Ikeda  in Tokyo at 
 iakiko@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
